Another church. Immaculate Conception Church in Batac, Ilocos Norte.

There are many churches in the province of Ilocos. Most of them are heritage sites that have stood through time. The stoned walls have stories to tell, the tale of the Philippines' historic north, which was of course about the Spanish influence during their rule of the country.

First stop, Bantay Church and Bell Tower, Ilocos Sur.

This was my first time to climb all the way to the top of a bell tower. The structure showed its age, though very well maintained. The view from the top was astounding. The sun rose over the mountain range that morning, and casted a shadow on the landscape beneath  it. The first of many more amazing sceneries to see.

"No  'meter os ps pelas mos', no significa ser rico ou ter pais ricos, no significa fugir dos problemas, ou da sua vida pacata. Viajar  tentar entender o mundo,  tentar conhecer as novas culturas, tentar conhecer a si mesmo. Viajar  abrir as possibilidades para novas experincias,  entender que existem outras formas de pensar e agir alm daquelas que voc conhece. Viajar  acordar com um mapa na mo, em um lugar estranho cujo o qual voc nem ao menos consegue pronunciar o nome.  passar por apertos e rir muito com seus amigos depois de tudo.  se entregar a natureza,  estar em paz consigo mesmo,  se apegar as coisas mais simples da vida a qual voc nunca deu valor antes. Viajar  descobrir que voc nunca esteve vivo,  descobrir que o mundo  muito grande para pensamentos to pequenos. Ento, permita-se, deixe de ser quem era, 'abandone as roupas velhas', renove-se!"

The Sacred Bridge ( shinky?) crossing the Daiya River belongs to the Futarasan Shrine. This beautiful vermilion lacquered structure is known as one of the three most beautiful bridges in Japan and is a perfect gateway for Nikko. The bridge was registered as a World Heritage in December 1999. Shinkyo measures 28 meters long, 7.4 meters wide, and stands 10.6 meters above the Daiya River. #wikipedia

Nikk ( Nikk-shi?, literally "sunlight" or "sunshine") is a city in the mountains of Tochigi Prefecture, Japan. Approximately 140 km north of Tokyo and 35 km west of Utsunomiya, the capital of Tochigi Prefecture, it is a popular destination for Japanese and international tourists. #wikipedia

The Great Buddha of Kamakura is a monumental outdoor bronze statue of Amitbha Buddha located at the Ktoku-in Temple in Kamakura, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan. The bronze statue probably dates from 1252, in the Kamakura period, according to temple records. #wikipedia

KAMAKURA 
There is beauty in all we know and beauty in all we don't know. Our journey is to love it all.  Thomas Warfield

The temple is built on two levels and also includes an underground cave. The grounds of the temple are home to hundreds of small Jiz statues, placed by parents mourning offspring lost to miscarriage, stillbirth, or abortion. #wikipedia

Sagami Bay ( Sagami-wan?, also known as the Sagami Gulf or Sagami Sea) lies south of Kanagawa Prefecture in Honshu, central Japan, contained within the scope of the Miura Peninsula, in Kanagawa, to the east, the Izu Peninsula, in Shizuoka Prefecture, to the west, and the Shnan coastline to the north, while the island of Izu shima marks the southern extent of the bay. It lies approximately 40 kilometres (25 mi) southwest of the capital, Tokyo. Cities on the bay include Odawara, Chigasaki, Fujisawa, Hiratsuka, Ito, and Kamakura. #wikipedia

SHORO BELFRY 
The temple originally belonged to the Tendai sect of Buddhism, but eventually became an independent temple of the Jdo sh sect. #wikipedia

Hase-dera ( Kaik-zan Jish-in Hase-dera?), commonly called the Hase-kannon (?) is one of the great Buddhist temples in the city of Kamakura in Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan, famous for housing a massive wooden statue of Kannon. The temple is the fourth of the 33 stations of the Band Sanjsankasho pilgrimage circuit dedicated to the goddess Benzaiten. #wikipedia

I miss India! 
#throwback #Kochi #Kerala #SouthIndia #INDIA #travel #travel2014 #travelinstyle 
Nasib setiap hamba Allah kat muka Bumi tak sama. Berlainan rezeki. Ada yang dapat lebih rezeki ada yang dapat kurang tp yang dapat kurang tu mesti Tuhan bagi kelebihan dari aspect lain mungkin. Sebab Allah itu maha Adil. Sama jugak dgn jodoh. Ada yg dapat jodoh cepat ada yang lambat. 
Dalam kehidupan seharian aku dan dikelilingi oleh insan2 yang selalu ckp mcm ni dkt aku, 'xpa la tak kahwin lg, bole p jalan2 merata. Sorang2 senang, xdak komitmen.' Errrr..aku sendiri pelik. Mereka2 ni tak pernah single ka. Lahir2 terus kahwin ka? Or tiba2 Bumi ni baru wujud nak dijelajah? Aku sendiri yg single ni komitmen byk jugak weii..Mcm hutang korang kena bayar macam tu jugak aku kena bayar. Dan kenapa nak dijadikan status perkahwinan itu sebagai halangan. Dan paling aku tak suka, anak dijadikan alasan. Alasannya susah nak jaga. Aku pernah jumpa 1 couple ni masa dekat Krabi. Best ja dorang p jalan2, n then tinggai anak kat mak bapak tlg jaga.  #typicalmalaysian
Aku tgk mat2 salleh OK ja bawa 1 family travel siap posing 1 dunia lg. Personally bagi aku, aku tak nak status perkahwinan tu sebagai halangan utk kita nak travel. Mungkin kadar per tahun utk kita keluar dari negara ni mungkin berkurang sedikit compare ketika masih single. Its better than nothing kan. Kalo dah sama2 minat travel, lg best kan. Dia jugak soulmate kita dia jugak travel partner kita.  Hopefully Alyah menang mlm ni. Bole bayar buat repair Audi Dato Ramli tu. Haha #AJL29

Tarsius bancanus saltator. Mamalia mungil ini juga dikenal sebagai tarsius Belitung karena keberadaannya endemik di area kepulauan Belitung. Si kecil satu ini saya kunjungi di penangkaran Tarsius di area Batu Mentas, sekitar 1 jam dari Tj. Pandan. Penangkaran ini baru mulai dibangun sekitar tiga tahun belakangan dengan dukungan donor dan pemda Belitung. Menurut IUCN, Tarsius b. saltator termasuk dalam kategori endangered atau terancam. Ketika berkunjung pemandu saya bercerita, upaya mengembangkanbiakkan mamalia ini belum berhasil. Mereka mencoba memasangkan jantan dan betina dalam satu kandang namun salah satu nya kemudian ditemukan mati. Diduga, gelombang ultrasonik penyebabnya. Tarsius bancanus, seperti sepupunya Tarsius syrichta (Tarsius Philippines) berkomunikasi melalui gelombang ultrasonik dalam frekuensi dominan 70 kHz - Tarsius syrichta bisa mencapai 91 kHz -  yang merupakan frekuensi tertinggi yang pernah di temukan dalam komunikasi mamalia terrestrial. #vscocam #Indonesiaonly #wonderfulIndonesia #travel2014

column10: At a 100 year old Parsi house in Panchgani, we realised that life was much more than chasing materialistic dreams. While an isolated 18th century Rajbari in rural Bengal took us back in time. Zipping through tiny hamlets in a bike, we discovered Goa beyond its crowded beaches filled with touristy shacks. And after innumerable trips to Alibag, this time we didn't miss visiting the old synagogue. Last but not the least, we made Turkey happen after an almost-jinxed plan. 2014, you have been kind in showing us the way. Literally! #yearoftravel #traveldiaries #havefeetwilltravel #travel2014 #holidays

BEDUGUL. This lakey area is one of the tourist destination in Bali. It is located at the center part of the island and can easily be reached from Denpasar or Kuta. The main tourist spot are the mountainous scenery and the misty lake. People are gathered near the lake to enjoy the chilly mountain atmosphere - contrast to what people are usually seeking for in Bali beaches - while having family picnic #vscocam #Indonesiaonly #travel2014

Hidden beach in Bali. We have to go through hundreds of stone staircase to get to the beach. There are some people already when we're there but they left soon as we arrive, practically making this pristine beach ours to enjoy :) #vscocam #Indonesiaonly #bali #travel2014

Next was 15k trail run at Sarwarna beach.

And Finally, I'm going to close this year and start 2015 in #Europe. Especially #Paris.

column10:
IKEBANA 
More than simply putting flowers in a container, ikebana is a disciplined art form in which nature and humanity are brought together. Contrary to the idea of floral arrangement as a collection of particolored or multicolored arrangement of blooms, ikebana often emphasizes other areas of the plant, such as its stems and leaves, and draws emphasis toward shape, line, form. Though ikebana is a creative expression, it has certain rules governing its form. The artist's intention behind each arrangement is shown through a piece's color combinations, natural shapes, graceful lines, and the usually implied meaning of the arrangement. #wikipedia

column10:
My Christmas present to myself came early: The photobook which I pieced together on Blurb came in the mail today, and I am stoked on life. Physical photo albums (and printing out pictures in general) became phased out in my household ever since I got my first digital camera in the early 00's (aka Facebook early days), so this was my attempt to bring some tactile/visual resonance back. I'd been blessed with a year full of travel, and this is a personal curation of some of my favourite places, moments, stories, and experiences in these locales. Hoping this is my first of many compilations!

Publishing: @blurb_books
Edits: @VSCO

column10: Day13 of #24travelmoments : This is indeed one of the scariest and depressing place I have ever been. At first, I don't even have the guts to look at my photos or any plans to post it online, but then I think that I should let the world see it and know about it. #S21 has been the security prison during the Khmer Rouge, but is now a museum and gallery about the past. Even they have cleaned the place, yet you can still see the horror and hear the screams of the people who were once detained in the area. People must know about this, and we must learn from it. column10:
For me, trees have always been the most penetrating preachers. I revere them when they live in tribes and families, in forests and groves. And even more I revere them when they stand alone. They are like lonely persons. 
Trees have long thoughts, long-breathing and restful, just as they have longer lives than ours. They are wiser than we are, as long as we do not listen to them. But when we have learned how to listen to trees, then the brevity and the quickness and the childlike hastiness of our thoughts achieve an incomparable joy. Whoever has learned how to listen to trees no longer wants to be a tree. He wants to be nothing except what he is. That is home. That is happiness.  Hermann Hesse

column10:
MT. FUJI 
Mount Fuji's exceptionally symmetrical cone, which is snow-capped several months a year, is a well-known symbol of Japan and it is frequently depicted in art and photographs, as well as visited by sightseers and climbers. It is one of Japan's "Three Holy Mountains" ( Sanreizan?) along with Mount Tate and Mount Haku; it is a Special Place of Scenic Beauty, a Historic Site, and was added to the World Heritage List as a Cultural Site on June 22, 2013. #wikipedia

column10:
WOODS OF NET
by japanese net artist Toshiko Horiuchi Macadam

The artist knitted the net entirely by hand, which is designed for children to crawl in, roll around, and jump on the net. It was easy for us to see the artwork being outside even when it cannot be exposed to rain or ultraviolet light.

http://www.archdaily.com/39223/woods-of-net-tezuka-architects/

WOODS OF NET
 a permanent pavilion for japanese net artist Toshiko Horiuchi Macadam, in collaboration with structural engineers TIS & PARTNERS.

The pavilion is located at the Hakone Open-Air Museum, a unique open museum located in one of the most visited tourist spots in Japan. Woods of Net was added to the collection of art works as part of their 40th anniversary.

http://www.archdaily.com/39223/woods-of-net-tezuka-architects/

column10:
Kyu-Yasuda Teien Gardens  

The Kyu-Yasuda Teien Gardens in Tokyo's Ryogoku district in Sumida ward are just north of the sumo stadium, the Kokugikan. Kyu-Yasuda Teien Gardens began life as the grounds of a samurai residence in 1691. The residence was famed for its pond that was fed by the Sumida River, running alongside the plot.

The Sumida being as close to the sea as it is was affected by the tides, causing the water level in the garden pond to rise and fall with it.

The land's 20th century inheritor, Yasuda Zenjiro, granted the land to the public after his death in 1922, but the Great Kanto Earthquake of September 1923 destroyed it. Renovation was complete by 1927 when it became a park.

Read more: http://www.japanvisitor.com/japan-parks-gardens/kyu-yasuda-teien-tokyo#ixzz3LCzHThxt

KANDA MYJIN SHRINE 
Kanda Shrine ( Kanda-myjin?, formerly  Kanda-jinja), is a Shinto shrine located in Chiyoda, Tokyo, Japan. The shrine dates back 1,270 years, but the current structure was rebuilt several times due to fire and earthquakes. It is situated in one of the most expensive estate areas of Tokyo. Kanda Shrine was an important shrine to both the warrior class and citizens of Japan, especially during the Edo period, when shogun Tokugawa Ieyasu paid his respects at Kanda Shrine. #wikipedia

SENS - JI PAGODA 
The t ( lit. pagoda?), sometimes also called butt ( lit. Buddhist pagoda?) or tba ( lit. pagoda?) is the Japanese version of the Chinese pagoda, itself an interpretation of the Indian stupa. Like the stupa, pagodas were originally used as reliquaries but, in many cases, as in Japan, they ended up losing this function. Pagodas are quintessentially Buddhist and an important component of Japanese Buddhist temple compounds but, because until the Kami and Buddhas Separation Act of 1868 a Shinto shrine was normally also a Buddhist temple and vice versa, they are not rare at shrines too. #wikipedia

SENS - JI TEMPLE 
Sens-ji is the focus of Tokyo's largest and most popular festival, Sanja Matsuri. This takes place over 34 days in late spring, and sees the surrounding streets closed to traffic from dawn until late evening.

column10:
TOKYO METRO STATION 
Tokyo Station ( Tky-eki?) is a railway station in the Marunouchi business district of Chiyoda, Tokyo, Japan, near the Imperial Palace grounds and the Ginza commercial district.

Served by Shinkansen high-speed rail lines, Tokyo Station is the main intercity rail terminal in Tokyo. It is the busiest station in Japan in terms of number of trains per day (over 3,000), and the fifth-busiest in Eastern Japan in terms of passenger throughput. It is also served by many regional commuter lines of Japan Railways, as well as the Tokyo Metro network. #wikipedia

NEZU SHRINE
Nezu Shrine was relocated to the Nezu area in the mid-17th century on the occasion of Shogun Tsunayoshi Tokugawa choosing his successor. Such is Nezu Shrine's status in history that it features not only in the doings of the Shoguns but of the Imperial family too. For example, when the Emperor moved his seat from Kyoto to Tokyo in the late nineteenth century, he sent envoys to Nezu Shrine to have the Shrine intercede with the gods on his behalf.

Read more: http://www.japanvisitor.com/japan-temples-shrines/nezu-shrine-tokyo#ixzz3KwQ2sAA3

TORII GATE 
A torii (?, lit. bird abode, /tri.i/) is a traditional Japanese gate most commonly found at the entrance of or within a Shinto shrine, where it symbolically marks the transition from the profane to the sacred (see Sacred-profane dichotomy). The presence of a torii at the entrance is usually the simplest way to identify Shinto shrines, and a small torii icon represents them on Japanese road maps.[note 1] They are however a common sight at Japanese Buddhist temples too, where they stand at the entrance of the temple's own shrine, called chinjusha (?, tutelary god shrine) and are usually very small. #Wikipedia

TORII PATHWAYS 
A particularly memorable feature of Nezu Shrine is its scores of small, vermilion torii Shinto shrine gates that cover the paths on the hillside above the main shrine, making for a tunnel effect.

The torii-lined pathways lead to and from a viewing platform that is part of the smaller Otome Inari Shrine, a shrine-within-a-shrine that overlooks the main shrine buildings, and over a sizable pond directly below.

If you take the path through the tunnel of torii that begins on your left after crossing the bridge, you will come across a pile of about half a dozen rocks placed somewhat randomly and fenced off. This is the Enazuka or "Placenta Mound" containing the afterbirth of Tokugawa Ienobu (1662  1712), the sixth Shogun of Japan.

Read more: http://www.japanvisitor.com/japan-temples-shrines/nezu-shrine-tokyo#ixzz3KslEeM7U

JAPANESE ARCHITECTURE 
The roof is the most visually impressive component, often constituting half the size of the whole edifice. The slightly curved eaves extend far beyond the walls, covering verandas, and their weight must therefore be supported by complex bracket systems called toky, in the case of temples and shrines. Simpler solutions are adopted in domestic structures. The oversize eaves give the interior a characteristic dimness, which contributes to the building's atmosphere. #wikipedia

AUXILIARY BUILDING Bentendo was built to ward off evil. The manmade lake became Shinobazu Ike (Shinobazu Pond). Tenkai Namboko, who also became the first head priest of Kan'ei-ji, arranged for a shrine to become the place of worship for Benten, or Benzaiten, the lute-playing goddess of Lake Biwa, one of the Seven Gods of Fortune. She is also the goddess of knowledge and wisdom and even today many visitor come here to pray for success with money and exams.

Sacrifice of a Goat for the Dashain Festival in Nepal, the biggest Hindu holiday. - I was Nagarkot for two days to see the amazing sunset and sunrise combined with the Himalayan peaks and also to have a glimpse at Mount Everest when the morning when i got for the sunrise i heard loud noises coming from a distance. I started climbing towards the voices and i saw a small temple and stairs leading to it. There were bunch of people, men, women, kids, all if them with their goats. I went up to the and asked what was going on, i have totally forgotten that it was their biggest festival and that this day they are sacrificing animals for their Gods. When the sun was up the slaughtering began. The sacrificed more than 50 goats and chicken in 15 minutes! I totally forgot about the sunrise and the peaks, as a person that is inspired by traditions and people, i was eager to learn more about the history of the festival and the sacrificing, they said that in the old days there were place where people were sacrificed. Dashain is the longest and most auspicious festival in the Nepalese calendar. The festival starts from the "Shukla Paksha" (bright lunar fortnight) of the month of Ashvin and ending on "Purnima", the full moon. Among the 15 days of celebration, the most important are the first, seventh, eight, ninth and the tenth. People return from all parts of the world, as well as the country, to celebrate together with the families. - #Dashain #Festival #Traditions #Nepal #Nepalese @lonelyplanet #lpfanphoto #LonelyPlanet #culture #Hindu #Nagarkot #Celebration #Sacrifice #documentary #photojournalism #photooftheday #people #gathering #religion @chenpamela  #neverstopexploring #travel #wanderlust #travel2014 #WHPwordstoimages #ReportageSpotlight #NgcOnAssignment

Hachiko..--He was an Akita dog that belonged to a professor at the University of Tokyo. Every day he would meet his master at Shibuya Station until one day the professor never returned. Not known to Hachiko, his master had suffered a fatal brain hemorrhage and would never come home again. But there Hachiko sat, day after day, waiting in vain for the return of his beloved master. #japan #travel2014 #hachiko

Gyeongbok Palace, is a royal palace located in northern Seoul, South Korea. First constructed in 1395, later burned and abandoned for almost three centuries, and then reconstructed in 1867, it was the main and largest palace of the Five Grand Palaces built by the Joseon Dynasty. The name means "Palace" [Gung] "Greatly Blessed by Heaven" [Gyeongbok]. #seoul #korea #autumngetaway #pasyalnikramrevilo #travel2014 #vacation #lifeisgood
